{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622743"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:06:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:06:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16823"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16823"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0.1,0,0.2,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9514"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76654"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9514"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16823"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62151"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7166"},{"type":"tags","id":"7178"},{"type":"tags","id":"7179"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22474"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22480"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76654"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe spinal cord grey matter demonstrates distinct anatomical variations at different vertebral levels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following spinal cord segments contains a lateral horn of grey matter?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["T12","L3","S4","C4","L5"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe lateral horn of grey matter is a distinct anatomical feature found only in specific segments of the spinal cord. \u003Cstrong\u003ET12\u003C/strong\u003E is within the thoracic region (T1-T12) where the lateral horn is consistently present, containing preganglionic sympathetic neurones that form part of the sympathetic nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EL3\u003C/strong\u003E is in the lumbar region below L2, where the lateral horn is not present. The lateral horn typically ends at the L2 level.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ES4\u003C/strong\u003E is in the sacral region. While this region contains preganglionic parasympathetic neurones, they are not organised into a distinct lateral horn formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC4\u003C/strong\u003E is in the cervical region where there is no lateral horn. The grey matter in cervical segments is characterised by large anterior horns containing motor neurones for upper limb muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EL5\u003C/strong\u003E is in the lower lumbar region where there is no lateral horn. This region has prominent anterior horns containing motor neurones for lower limb muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of the lateral horn in thoracic and upper lumbar segments reflects the distribution of sympathetic outflow to the body. Understanding this anatomical arrangement is crucial for comprehending autonomic nervous system organisation and function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The lateral horn of grey matter is present only in thoracic (T1-T12) and upper lumbar (L1-L2) segments of the spinal cord.","The lateral horn contains preganglionic sympathetic neurones in thoracic segments.","The distribution of the lateral horn reflects the anatomical organisation of sympathetic outflow to the body."],"references":["Harrow-Mortelliti M, Reddy V, Jimsheleishvili G. Physiology, Spinal Cord. 2023 Mar 17. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31334987","Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62151"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16823"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62151"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T20:18:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T20:20:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9514"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76654"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups"